Energy Trading Database Analysis (SQL)
Project Overview

This project simulates an energy trading analytics environment using MySQL.

The objective is to design a relational database, generate realistic electricity market data, and perform SQL-based analysis to answer business questions related to:

electricity market prices
trading activity
trader performance
market positions
profitability analysis

The project focuses on SQL skills required for entry-level Energy Market Analyst, BI Analyst, and Data Analyst roles.

Business Context

Energy trading companies monitor electricity markets, trading activity, and portfolio performance to make data-driven decisions.

This project represents a simplified trading environment where:

traders execute BUY and SELL energy transactions
different assets participate in electricity markets
market prices fluctuate hourly
trading performance is evaluated using SQL analytics
Database Design

The database follows a relational model consisting of dimension and fact tables.

Dimension Tables
traders

Contains information about trading participants.

Columns:

trader_id
trader_name
desk
country
markets

Contains electricity market information.

Columns:

market_id
market_name
market_type
country
assets

Contains generation assets.

Columns:

asset_id
asset_name
asset_type
capacity_mw
renewable
Fact Tables
market_prices

Hourly electricity market price data.

Contains:

market_id
price_timestamp
settlement_price
hour
peak_type

Dataset size:

8,760 hourly observations
Full year of simulated market prices

The dataset includes:

peak/off-peak behavior
seasonal effects
price spikes
negative price events
trades

Simulated energy trading transactions.

Contains:

trader_id
market_id
asset_id
trade_date
trade_timestamp
trade_type (BUY/SELL)
volume_mwh
price

Dataset size:

50,000 trading transactions
Data Generation

Market and trading datasets were generated using Python and exported as CSV files.

Python was used only for:

synthetic data generation
data preparation
CSV creation

The main analysis was performed using MySQL SQL queries.

